&lt;h2 id=&#34;emmett-till&#34;&gt;Emmett Till&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;norman-rockwell&#34;&gt;Norman Rockwell&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Norman Rockwell (1894-1978) was an American painter, known for his generally popular (though often not critically acclaimed) portraits of mid-century American life. We discussed two of his paintings - &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saying_Grace_(Rockwell)&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Saying Grace&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (1951) and &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Problem_We_All_Live_With&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Problem We all Live With&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (1964), the latter of which captures four U.S. Marshals escorting &lt;a href=&#34;#ruby-bridges&#34;&gt;Ruby Bridges&lt;/a&gt; to elementary school in New Orleans during that city&amp;rsquo;s school desegregation crisis. If you&amp;rsquo;re ever in Western Massachusetts, you can stop and see the &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.nrm.org&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Norman Rockwell Museum&lt;/a&gt;, dedicated to preserving his works and legacy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;ruby-bridges&#34;&gt;Ruby Bridges&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-vietnam-war&#34;&gt;The Vietnam War&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A long-running conflict, which the U.S. was involved in from November, 1955 through April, 1975. The war itself is a massive and contraverseal topic in the U.S. You can get a brief overview of the conflict &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vietnam_War&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;on Wikipedia&lt;/a&gt; and a more in-depth introduction with &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Burns&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Ken Burn&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/a&gt; 2017 documentary &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Vietnam_War_(TV_series)&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Vietnam War&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. I also recommend reading &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_O%27Brien_(author)&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Tim O&amp;rsquo;Brien&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/a&gt; books for an infantry soldier&amp;rsquo;s literary perspective, and watching &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fog_of_War&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Fog of War&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; for a political perspective on Secretary of Defense &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_McNamara&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Robert McNamara&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;other-figures&#34;&gt;Other Figures&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We also briefly mentioned:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;President &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_F._Kennedy&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;John F. Kennedy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Arkansas Gov. &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Wallace&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;George Wallace&lt;/a&gt;, a segregationist who challenged LBJ in the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1964_Democratic_Party_presidential_primaries&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;1964 Democratic primary&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
